plete to tricorn hat and leggings, strode up beside the mortar.\par
"I cain't understand what all this here fussin' is about," he drawled.\par
At this, Officer Riley drew himself erect and demanded, "And who do you think you are in that rig?"\par
The old man smiled and his weather-beaten face creased into long lines. He told Officer Riley that he was Jim Tilton, a retired artillery sergeant of the National Guard. He had been asked by Police Chief Collig to take charge of the Independence Day cannon salute. "An* I think I look 'propriate for this job," he added.\par
"But this ain't the Fourth!" Riley protested. "It's only the first. Why should you come around here bombardin' the town without warnin?"\par
The old-timer raised his hands good-naturedly. "I'm mighty sorry I caused so much fuss. After all, I wasn't usin' a ball. I just had some powder an' waddin' in her."\par
Tilton pulled a letter from his pocket and showed it to the officers. It was from Chief Collig and the Fourth-of-July Committee, granting permission for Tilton to test the mortar.\par
"Well, there was no harm done," Riley said, "but I should have been notified. But anyway, we know the gun is ready-we and everybody for five miles around!"\par
Reassured, the crowd dispersed as Officers Smuff\par
A Suspicious Client 13\par
and Riley herded them off. Sergeant Tilton remained near the mortar, talking with a few men. The Hardys moved closer to get a better look at the old sergeant and the equipment he had been using.\par
Bowden also edged forward and stared with keen interest at the various markings on the gun. He told the boys that this was a Federal piece.\par
"It was cast at the same arsenal that turned out the famous 'Dictator,' " he said. "That was a thirteen-inch mortar used against Petersburg, Virginia, in the Civil War."\par
Tilton raised his eyebrows in surprise. "Land sakes," he remarked, "you know a lot! An' here I am, a veteran of that famous battle between the \i Monitor \i0 an' the \i Merrimac, \i0 an' I didn't never suspect anything like that about this ol' hunk o' iron."\par
Everyone laughed and Joe quickly calculated that for Tilton's tall tale to be true he would have to be well over a hundred years old.\par
As the sergeant began to clean the barrel of the old weapon, Bowden turned to Frank and Joe. "My offer to you," he said in a low voice, "is one thousand dollars if you find the Spanish cannon."\par
Frank and Joe were amazed. A thousand dollars for an old gun to be used in a pageant!\par
Sensing their thoughts, Bowden quickly added, "I'm a man of means and can well afford it."\par
He explained that he had already combed\par
14 The Secret of Pirates' Hill\par
Bayport proper. The boys' responsibility would lie in searching the surrounding areas and nearby towns. Bowden said he was staying at the Garden Gate Motel on the state highway and could be reached there if anything developed.\par
"We don't charge for our sleuthing," Frank informed the man.\par
Bowden was astonished. "You've solved all your cases for nothing?"\par
Joe nodded. "If we should help you," he said, "it will be on that basis."\par
"Okay. But believe me, I'll make it worth your while somehow!" Then, seeing that Tilton was preparing to leave, Bowden hastily excused himself. "I have a few questions to ask this old codger. See you later."\par
"Okay, Mr. Bowden," Frank replied. "We'll think about your request and let you know our decision."\par
The Hardys crossed the square and headed for the police station to report the underwater attack on them. They went directly to Chief Collig, a solidly built man in his late forties. He often co-operated with the Hardys on their cases, and now listened intently to their latest adventure.\par
"This is serious," he said. "I'll notify the harbor patrol to be on the lookout for a skin diver wearing a black suit and a swim cap with a yellow stripe around it."\par
The boys thanked him and left. As they walked\par
A Suspicious Client 15\par
up Elm Street on which they lived, their conversation turned to Bowden.\par
"It seems that we're back in business!" Joe remarked. "Let's take on the case."\par
"I'm a little worried about it," Frank replied. "The whole setup seems a bit phony."\par
"You're imagining things, Frank. Bowden's a nice fellow."\par
Joe was naturally impulsive and always ready for action. Frank reminded him of the many times they had met people who had seemed to be aboveboard yet had turned out to be dishonest.\par
"But we'd still have fun looking for the cannon," Joe insisted. "What could we lose?"\par
"Nothing, maybe."\par
At the rambling stone house in which they lived, the boys were greeted by their petite mother and their tall, angular Aunt Gertrude. She was Mr. Hardy's sister, and spent most of her time at his house. When she heard about Clyde Bowden's offer, Aunt Gertrude exclaimed tartly:\par
"A thousand dollars for finding an old piece of junk! There's something underhanded about such a deal. Mark my words!"\par
Mrs. Hardy's face wore a worried frown. "I wish your father were here to take the case," she said, "instead of being in Florida."\par
"Florida!" Joe exclaimed. "Frank, Dad could check on Bowden's credentials. Let's phone him!"\par
16 The Secret of Pirates' Hill\par
Mrs. Hardy said the detective could be reached only by telegram at an address in Miami. Frank wrote it down and hurriedly sent a wire.\par
"We may not get an answer for several days," Joe remarked. "I hate to wait. Why can't we make a start on Bowden's case? We can drop it any time we like."\par
"Okay, but let's not get in too deep until we hear from Dad."\par
"I'll let Bowden know," said Joe. He dialed the Garden Gate Motel. Bowden was not in, so Joe left a message for him. Then he turned to Frank. "What say we advertise in the newspaper for information about the demiculverin?"\par
"Good idea." Another call placed a query in the classified section of the Bayport \i Times, \i0 which had a wide circulation in the smaller outlying towns.\par
"Now we're getting some place!" Joe exulted. "Say, maybe Aunt Gertrude can help us."\par
"How?"\par
"As newly elected president of the Bayport Historical Society," Joe said, "she might have some information about ancient cannon in the vicinity."\par
Their aunt had gone to the kitchen to start preparations for lunch, so the boys went out there and put the question to her. After a moment's thought, Miss Hardy said, "I know of one cannon."\par
A Suspicious Client 17\par
"Where is it?" Joe asked eagerly.\par
"Let me see- I think it's on the back lawn of a museum in Greenville."\par
"Do you know what type it is?" Frank asked.\par
"I think it may be pre-Civil War," Aunt Gertrude replied. "It might be Spanish. I'm not sure."\par
"We'll take a look," said Joe.\par
After lunch the boys set off in their convertible for the Greenville Museum. It was a small building on the corner of two roads at the edge of town. The main entrance was on one road, with a tall hedge in front of the building. Extensive grounds stretched to the rear on the side road, along which ran a high, iron picket fence. Frank parked in front alongside the hedge, and the brothers walked through a gate to the spacious lawn at the back.\par
The cannon, a long-barreled six-pounder, stood in the center of the plot. Joe dashed across the flagstones leading to it and read the plaque fixed to the piece.\par
"It's a Spanish gun!"\par
Frank joined him and read the inscription on the bronze plaque. It stated:\par
\i "Pasavolante, \i0 meaning fast action. Made in Toledo, Spain. Often called \i cerbatana, \i0 after Cerebus, the fierce dog of mythology. \i Pasavolante \i0 in modern Spanish means peashooter."\par
"Do you suppose this could be the peashooter\par
18 The Secret of Pirates' Hill\par
that Bowden is searching for and he just got the name wrong?" Joe asked.\par
"I doubt it," Frank answered. "Bowden seemed sure it was a demiculverin."\par
"False clue." Joe sighed.\par
As the brothers started back across the lawn, they noticed a tall, slender man, with a swarthy complexion, entering from a side gate. Bareheaded and wearing a black cotton motorcycle jacket, he moved hurriedly toward the gun.\par
Casting backward glances, the boys watched him as they continued to the roadway. Now the man was kneeling at the \i pasavolante. \i0 Frank and Joe paused long enough to watch him rise and run to the far side of the cannon to scrutinize it.\par
"Maybe we're not the only ones trying to locate a demiculverin," Joe remarked. "Let's go back and question that fellow."\par
Retracing their steps, they had covered only a few feet when the man suddenly ran for the *ide gate by which he had entered.\par
"He must be goofy," Joe remarked.\par
The brothers turned back and hurried to the road. The next moment, they heard a motorcycle roar into action.\par
The swarthy stranger, goggles over his eyes, sped around the corner. He headed directly toward the boys!\par
CHAPTER III\par
\i A Motorcycle Clue\i0\par
As the motorcycle roared down on them, Frank and Joe leaped aside and stumbled headlong into the hedge. The driver missed them by inches!\par
"Sorry!" he shouted and sped off.\par
The boys picked themselves up. Both were angry.\par
"Did that lunatic mean he was sorry he didn't hit us?" Joe stormed.\par
"I'd like to get my hands on him!" Frank said. "Look at my trousers!" The sharp twigs of the hedge had made a long tear in them.\par
"Did you get his license number?" Joe asked.\par
"No," Frank answered ruefully. "But the motorcycle looked like a foreign make. I saw the letter K on the rear fender."\par
"If I ever see that fellow again, he'll have some explaining to do as to why he nearly hit us/' said\par
20 The Secret of Pirates' Hill\par
Joe. "And I'd like to ask him about his interest in the old cannon, too."\par
"He certainly acted as if he was afraid somebody might notice what he was doing," said Frank.\par
When the boys reached home they hurried into the kitchen. Aunt Gertrude was just removing a batch of cookies from the oven. She glanced over her spectacles and exclaimed, "No need to charge in here like a herd of buffalo!"\par
"We smelled the cookies and couldn't wait to have some," Joe said with a grin, as he reached for the tray of hot gingersnaps.\par
This subtle flattery softened the maiden lady's stern demeanor. "Well, in that case, have one," she said. "But don't eat them too fast or you'll get indigestion."\par
"Indigestion!" Frank cried out. "What did you do? Bake rocks in 'em?"\par
Aunt Gertrude gave her nephew a withering look. Although she would be the last person to admit it, she enjoyed the boys' teasing. But to hear her scold and correct them, a listener might think Frank and Joe were the bane of her existence. Aunt Gertrude's peppery manner, however, concealed a great depth of affection for them.\par
"Frank!" she sputtered. "You've torn your trousers!"\par
"Had a little accident," he admitted, and told her of the motorcyclist.\par
A Motorcycle Clue 21\par
"I knew it!" Miss Hardy said firmly. "Hoodlums are after you two again. Stay away from such people!"\par
Frank suppressed a chuckle while Aunt Gertrude took another tray of cookies from the oven. "You wouldn't want us to let 'em run around loose, would you?" he teased.\par
"Well, don't say I didn't warn you." His aunt sighed. "Trouble, trouble," she added to herself.\par
"What trouble?" Frank asked.\par
"The Bayport Historical Society," Aunt Gertrude replied. "What would you do with a case full of swords?"\par
Frank nearly choked on a cookie. "Swords!"\par
"Yes, cutlasses. I'd like to keep them."\par
"Please, Aunty, start from the beginning," Joe begged, "and tell us about it."\par
Aunt Gertrude explained that the Bayport Historical Society had recently received a gift from the estate of Senator Entwistle. It included some lovely old costumes dating from 1812 and a case of cutlasses.\par
"I argued with our members," Aunt Gertrude went on, "but they insist that we present the cutlasses to the museum at the state capitol."\par
"Too bad," said Frank, then asked, "Is it your job to have them shipped?"\par
"Yes," she replied. "But the cutlasses are to be moved to the basement temporarily. The museum isn't ready to receive them."\par
22 The Secret of Pirates' Hill\par
"And you'd like us to help you," the boys said in unison.\par
"Yes. Tomorrow evening."\par
"We'll be there."\par
Frank and Joe went to their room and sat down to discuss the next move in locating the cannon which Bowden wanted.\par
"We can't do anything today out of town," said Frank, glancing at the table clock between the boys' beds. "It's almost time for dinner."\par
"There's something we \i can \i0 do," Joe spoke up. "Visit the motorcycle shops in Bayport and find out the name of the foreign make with a K."\par
"Good idea, Joe. We may even learn the identity of that fellow who nearly ran us down."\par
"What are we waiting for? Let's go!" Joe urged.\par
The boys had better luck than they had anticipated. The first dealer they called on explained that the letter K indicated the motorcycle was the Kesselring, a German make.\par
"You don't see many of them around," he said. "But they're becoming more popular."\par
"Do you sell them?" Frank asked.\par
"No."\par
"Who does?"\par
"Nobody in Bayport. And no one in town owns one, either."\par
"Do you know where the nearest agency is located?" Frank asked.\par
"Yes," the dealer replied. "In Delmore."\par
A Motorcycle Clue 23\par
"That's where the penitentiary is," Joe remarked.\par
The man nodded. "The dealer there mostly sells bikes, but he took on the Kesselring motorcycle agency because the machines come from his native country."\par
The Hardys exchanged glances. Had the man they had seen on a Kesselring bought his motorcycle in Delmore? The boys thanked the dealer and rode off in their convertible.\par
"What say we drive over to Delmore in the morning and talk to that agent?" Joe suggested.\par
"We'll do it," Frank agreed. "The main road there is still closed. The detour leads past the Entwistle place where the cutlasses came from."\par
At home the boys were greeted by the aroma of fried chicken that their mother was preparing.\par
"You're just in time," she said, smiling.\par
The boys washed, then followed Mrs. Hardy and Aunt Gertrude to the table.\par
